more diverse team?

00:45:52.175 --> 00:45:54.550
NICOLE FARKOUH: The vendor
pipeline you're talking about?

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:54.820
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:45:54.820 --> 00:45:55.240
NICOLE FARKOUH: OK.

00:45:55.240 --> 00:45:56.440
JENNIFER BROWN: And the
hiring on the vendor

00:45:56.440 --> 00:45:57.727
side, like their own hiring?

00:45:57.727 --> 00:45:58.310
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:45:58.310 --> 00:46:00.580
JENNIFER BROWN: Yeah.

00:46:00.580 --> 00:46:05.050
Yeah, it is difficult. You're
constrained geographically

00:46:05.050 --> 00:46:05.590
from--

00:46:05.590 --> 00:46:06.910
and what age are you hiring?

00:46:06.910 --> 00:46:10.090
Like, out of school or
more experienced hires,

00:46:10.090 --> 00:46:11.010
all of the above?

00:46:11.010 --> 00:46:11.550
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
all of the above.

00:46:11.550 --> 00:46:13.000
JENNIFER BROWN: All the above.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:14.980
Yeah, because the answer
is kind of different

00:46:14.980 --> 00:46:18.760
when you're looking at
young hiring out of schools.

00:46:18.760 --> 00:46:21.730
We always say, are you looking
at a broad array of schools?

00:46:21.730 --> 00:46:25.000
Are you looking at a-- are you
throwing the job description

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.180
away and thinking more broadly
about the kinds of capabilities

00:46:28.180 --> 00:46:30.970
that you're looking for to
the nontraditional talent?

00:46:30.970 --> 00:46:33.340
And that means hiring
across difference usually.

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:35.170
If your founder team
is largely maybe

00:46:35.170 --> 00:46:37.240
white and male or
Asian and male,

00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:40.820
it's going to mean that
they have to be committed

00:46:40.820 --> 00:46:43.870
and to I wouldn't say take a
risk, because I don't believe

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:47.530
it's risky to hire
outside of your own image,

00:46:47.530 --> 00:46:49.310
but they will
believe that it is.

00:46:49.310 --> 00:46:53.170
And so how do we help them
understand that actually hiring

00:46:53.170 --> 00:46:56.680
in your own image can harm
your ability to be innovative

00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:59.470
and to generate that creative
abrasion that happens

00:46:59.470 --> 00:47:02.500
from that diversity of talent.

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:05.450
And I think you've got to
start with that resistance may

00:47:05.450 --> 00:47:09.580
be there, to then kind of
taking some leaps of faith

00:47:09.580 --> 00:47:13.240
and looking under corners that
you wouldn't have normally.

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:15.910
And even going so
far as to say I

00:47:15.910 --> 00:47:20.640
don't want to interview
if the pipeline has--

00:47:20.640 --> 00:47:23.170
I mean, I have a friend, Adam
Pisoni, who founded Yammer.

00:47:23.170 --> 00:47:24.920
I don't know if any
of you know who he is.

00:47:24.920 --> 00:47:25.900
He sold to Microsoft.

00:47:25.900 --> 00:47:28.270
His next startup, he
refuses to interview

00:47:28.270 --> 00:47:32.050
white, straight men like him.

00:47:32.050 --> 00:47:34.390
So literally they're not even
getting into the pipeline.

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:35.390
He refuses.

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:38.020
He said, if we let
any of that happen,

00:47:38.020 --> 00:47:40.390
it's going to end up that
our founding team, which

00:47:40.390 --> 00:47:43.280
is an education startup, by
the way, so serving schools,

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:47.849
is going to be, again,
kind of largely male.

00:47:47.849 --> 00:47:49.390
And he's, like, I'm
not OK with that,

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:53.260
and so I've got to take some
drastic action about even who

00:47:53.260 --> 00:47:57.130
I let into the pipeline to be
interviewed because there are

00:47:57.130 --> 00:47:58.910
so many male candidates
that come his way

00:47:58.910 --> 00:48:00.850
and not a lot of
diverse candidates.

00:48:00.850 --> 00:48:04.060
And so he's had to literally
kind of say to the team,

00:48:04.060 --> 00:48:07.720
this is a non-negotiable for
me, because this founding team

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:09.730
is so important
because who you hire

00:48:09.730 --> 00:48:11.934
is then going to send a
signal to your next hires

00:48:11.934 --> 00:48:13.600
and your next hires
and your next hires.

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:17.330
So literally what you do
when you're small really,

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:20.045
really matters, because it
will make your job so much

00:48:20.045 --> 00:48:20.920
easier in the future.

00:48:20.920 --> 00:48:23.170
So you have to be
uncompromising.

00:48:23.170 --> 00:48:26.740
You might want to put
some metrics in place,

00:48:26.740 --> 00:48:29.380
and then think outside the box.

00:48:29.380 --> 00:48:33.070
Watch out also for gendered
language in job descriptions.

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:35.590
Really interesting, there
are some fascinating startups

00:48:35.590 --> 00:48:36.520
that are going on.

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:39.280
Unitive is one.

00:48:39.280 --> 00:48:42.922
Textio, Text.io is one, that
it literally goes through

00:48:42.922 --> 00:48:45.130
and looks at your job
descriptions and flags gendered

00:48:45.130 --> 00:48:46.760
language.

00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:49.900
And that keeps basically women
and nontraditional candidates

00:48:49.900 --> 00:48:51.720
away from even
applying for things.

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:54.460
So the way that
we describe roles

00:48:54.460 --> 00:48:59.590
is gendered and begins that
process of bias that screens--

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:03.010
people self-screen out because
if you're looking for a rock

00:49:03.010 --> 00:49:06.357
star coder, you're using
all this kind of language

00:49:06.357 --> 00:49:07.940
and women are like,
eh, that's not me.

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:09.820
I just don't see myself in that.

00:49:09.820 --> 00:49:10.900
NICOLE FARKOUH: Especially
if you're an introvert.

00:49:10.900 --> 00:49:12.090
JENNIFER BROWN: Especially
if you're an introvert.

00:49:12.090 --> 00:49:12.640
Exactly.

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:16.540
And my brilliant introvert--
so it really-- there's so many

00:49:16.540 --> 00:49:19.600
places bias occurs, I think,
that keeps your pipeline

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:23.050
from being welcoming
to even think

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:24.460
of themselves as applying.

00:49:24.460 --> 00:49:27.129
And so it's a long--
we can talk afterwards.

00:49:27.129 --> 00:49:28.170
There's a lot more ideas.

00:49:28.170 --> 00:49:30.820
And there's a lot of ideas
in here too of how to do it.

